==Notes and references==
===Notes===
* '''a.''' {{Note label|a|a|none}}Pronunciation: The story of the battle has been retold many times in English, from the fifteenth-century [[Agincourt Carol|Agincourt song]] onwards, and an English pronunciation of {{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|dʒ|ᵻ|ŋ|k|ɔːr|t}} has become established. [[Merriam-Webster]] has a small audio file here.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/cgi-bin/audio.pl?ggazin02.wav=Agincourt |title=Agincourt |work=Merriam-Webster Pronunciation |accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref> The modern tendency, however, is to use a style closer to the original {{IPA-fr|azɛ̃kuʁ}}, such as {{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|dʒ|ᵻ|ŋ|k|ɔːr}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|ʒ|ᵻ|ŋ|k|ʊər}},<ref>{{cite book|last=Olausson |first=Lena |author2=Sangster, Catherine |others= |title=Oxford BBC Guide to Pronunciation: The Essential Handbook of the Spoken Word|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford, England|year=2006|page=7|quote='''aj'''-in-kor/ˈadʒɪnˌkɔː(r)/ the established anglicization|isbn=978-0-19-280710-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Daniel|title=English Pronouncing Dictionary|editor=Roach, Peter|display-editors=etal|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|location=Cambridge, England|year=2003|edition=16th|page=12|isbn=978-0-521-01712-1}}</ref> as exampled in this interview with [[Juliet Barker]] on ''Meet the Author'', here.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.meettheauthor.co.uk/bookbites/915.html |title=Juliet Barker |work=Meet the Author |accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref>
* '''b.''' {{Note label|b|b|none}}Dates in the fifteenth century are difficult to reconcile with modern calendars: see {{harvnb|Barker|2005|pp=225–7}} for the way the date of the battle was established.
* '''c.''' {{Note label|c|c|none}}The first known use of angled stakes to thwart a mounted charge was at the Battle of Nicopolis, an engagement between European states and Turkish forces in 1396, twenty years before Agincourt. French knights, charging uphill, were unseated from their horses, either because their mounts were injured on the stakes or because they dismounted to uproot the obstacles, and were overpowered. News of the contrivance circulated within Europe and was described in a book of tactics written in 1411 by [[Jean le Maingre|Boucicault]], Marshal of France.{{sfn|Bennett|1994|pp=7, 15–16}}

