El Alamein was an Allied victory,<!--''Decisive'' isn't supported by the citation--> although Rommel did not lose hope until the end of the [[Tunisia Campaign]]. Churchill said,

{{quote|It may almost be said, "Before Alamein we never had a victory. After Alamein we never had a defeat".|sign=Winston Churchill.<ref>The Hinge of Fate, Winston Churchill, Pg 603. The Yale Book of Quotations By Fred Shapiro, Page 154.</ref>}}

The Allies frequently had numerical superiority in the Western Desert but never had it been so complete in quantity and quality. With the arrival of [[M4 Sherman|Sherman tanks]], [[Ordnance QF 6 pounder|6-pounder]] anti-tank guns and [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfires]] in the Western Desert, the Allies gained a comprehensive superiority.<ref name= "Playfair76">{{harvnb|Playfair||p=76}}</ref> Montgomery envisioned the battle as an attrition operation, similar to those fought in [[World War I]] and correctly predicted the length of the battle and the number of Allied casualties.<ref name=ham>{{cite book|chapter=Montgomery, Bernard Law|first=Nigel| last=Hamilton|title=[[Dictionary of National Biography|Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2004}}</ref> Allied artillery was superbly handled and Allied air support was excellent, in contrast to the ''Luftwaffe'' and ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]'', which offered little or no support to ground forces, preferring to engage in air-to-air combat. Air supremacy had a huge effect on the battle and not only because of its physical impact. As Montgomery later wrote,

{{quote|The moral effect of air action [on the enemy] is very great and out of all proportion to the material damage inflicted. In the reverse direction, the sight and sound of our own air forces operating against the enemy have an equally satisfactory effect on our own troops. A combination of the two has a profound influence on the most important single factor in war—morale.|Montgomery<ref name="Playfair63"/>}}

===Casualties===
[[File:El Alamein Aussie 9th edited.JPG|Memorial to the [[Australian 9th Division|9th Australian Division]] at the El Alamein Cemetery|thumb]]
In 2005, Barr wrote that the {{nowrap|36,939 men}} ''Panzerarmee'' casualties, was an estimate because of the chaos of the Axis retreat. British figures, based on Ultra intercepts, gave German casualties as {{nowrap|1,149 killed,}} {{nowrap|3,886 wounded}} and {{nowrap|8,050 men}} captured. Italian losses were {{nowrap|971 dead,}} {{nowrap|933 wounded}} and {{nowrap|15,552 men}} captured. By 11 November, the number of Axis prisoners had risen to {{nowrap|30,000 men.}}<ref name="Barr, 2005, p. 404">{{harvnb|Barr|2005|p=404}}</ref> In a note to ''The Rommel Papers'', [[Fritz Bayerlein]] (quoting figures obtained from ''Offizieller Bericht des Oberkommandos Afrika'') instead estimated German losses in the battle as 1,100 killed, 3,900 wounded and 7,900 prisoners and Italian losses as 1,200 killed, 1,600 wounded and 20,000 prisoners.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/THEROMMELPAPERS/THE%20ROMMEL%20PAPERS_djvu.txt The Rommel Papers]</ref>

According to the official history of the Italian Army, Axis losses during the battle were 4,000 to 5,000 killed or missing, 7,000 to 8,000 wounded and 17,000 prisoners; during the retreat the losses rose to 9,000 killed or missing, 15,000 wounded and 35,000 prisoners.{{sfn|Montanari|1993|p=838}} According to the writings of General Giuseppe Rizzo, total Axis casualties included 25,000 men killed or wounded (including 5,920 Italians killed) and 30,000 prisoners (20,000 Italians and 10,724 Germans), as well as 510 tanks and 2,000 field guns, anti-tank guns, anti-aircraft guns.<ref>Giuseppe Rizzo, ''Buche e croci nel deserto'', Verona, 1969, p. 549.</ref> Axis tank losses were {{circa|500;}} on 4 November, only {{nowrap|36 German}} tanks were left out of the {{nowrap|249 at}} the beginning of the battle. About half of the {{nowrap|278 Italian}} tanks had been lost and most of the remainder were knocked out on the next day by the 7th Armoured Division.<ref>{{harvnb|Playfair|2004|pp=78–79}}</ref> About {{nowrap|254 Axis}} guns were lost, along with {{nowrap|64 German}} and {{nowrap|20 Italian}} aircraft.<ref name="Barr, 2005, p. 404"/><ref name="Playfair, 2004, p. 78">{{harvnb|Playfair|2004|p=78}}</ref>

The Eighth Army had {{nowrap|13,560 casualties,}} of whom {{nowrap|2,350 men}} had been killed, {{nowrap|8,950 wounded}} and {{nowrap|2,260 men}} were missing; {{nowrap|58 percent}} of the casualties were British, {{nowrap|22 percent}} Australian, {{nowrap|10 percent}} New Zealanders, {{nowrap|6 percent}} South African, {{nowrap|1 percent}} Indian and {{nowrap|3 percent}} were Allied forces.<ref name="Playfair, 2004, p. 78"/> The Eighth Army lost from {{nowrap|332–500}} tanks, although by the end of the battle, {{nowrap|300}} had already been repaired.<ref>{{harvnb|Playfair|2004|pp=404, 78}}</ref> The artillery lost {{nowrap|111 guns}} and the DAF lost {{nowrap|77 British}} and {{nowrap|20 American}} aircraft.<ref name="Playfair, 2004, p. 78"/>

===Subsequent operations===
The Eighth Army was surprised by Rommel's withdrawal and confusion caused by redeployments between the three corps meant they were slow in pursuit, failing to cut off Rommel at Fuka and [[Mersa Matruh]].<ref>{{harvnb|Watson|2007|p=30}}</ref> The Desert Air Force failed to make a maximum effort to bomb a disorganised and retreating opponent, which on 5 November was within range and confined to the coast road. Supply shortages and a belief that the ''Luftwaffe'' were about to get strong reinforcements, led the DAF to be cautious, reduce the number of offensive sorties on 5 November and protect the Eighth Army.{{sfn|Hinsley|1981|pp=452–453}}

====Battle of El Agheila====
{{main article|Battle of El Agheila}}

[[File:WesternDesertBattle Area1941 en.svg|thumb|upright=1.6|Area of [[Western Desert Campaign]] 1941–1942]]
The Axis made a fighting withdrawal to El Agheila but Rommel's troops found themselves exhausted and with few replacements, while Montgomery had planned to transport material over great distances, to provide the [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]] with {{convert|2400|t|ST|abbr=on}} of supplies per day.<ref>{{harvnb|Clifford|1943|p=317}}</ref> Huge quantities of engineer stores had been collected to repair transport infrastructure and the railway line from El Alamein to Fort Capuzzo, despite having been blown up in over 200 places, was quickly repaired. In the month after Eighth Army reached Capuzzo, the railway carried {{convert|133000|ST|t|abbr=on}} of supplies.<ref name="AC318">{{harvnb|Clifford|1943|p=318}}</ref> Benghazi handled {{convert|3000|ST|t|abbr=on}} a day by the end of December, rather than the expected {{convert|800|ST|t|abbr=on}}.<ref name= "AC318"/>

Mindful of Axis counter-strokes from El Agheila, Montgomery paused for three weeks to concentrate his forces and prepare an assault.<ref>{{harvnb|Watson|2007|p=39}}</ref> On 11 December, Montgomery launched the [[51st (Highland) Division]] along the line of the coast road with [[7th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|7th Armoured Division]] on the inland flank. On 12 December the [[2nd New Zealand Division]] started a deeper flanking manouevre to cut the Axis line of retreat on coast road in the rear of the Mersa Brega position.<ref>{{harvnb|Watson|2007|p=42}}</ref> The Highland Division made a slow and costly advance and 7th Armoured met stiff resistance from the ''Ariete'' Combat Group (the remains of the ''Ariete'' Armoured Division). Rommel's army had lost roughly 75,000 men, 1,000 guns and 500 tanks since the Second battle of Alamein and withdrew.<ref>{{harvnb|Clifford|1943|p=319}}</ref> By 15 December, the New Zealanders had reached the coast road but the firm terrain allowed Rommel to break his forces into smaller units and withdraw off-road, through the gaps between the New Zealanders positions.<ref name="Wa43">{{harvnb|Watson|2007|p=43}}</ref>

Rommel conducted a text-book retreat, destroying all equipment and infrastructure left behind and peppering the land behind him with mines and booby traps.<ref>{{harvnb|Clifford|1943|pp=322, 320}}</ref> Eighth Army reached [[Sirte]] on 25 December but west of Sirte, were forced to pause to consolidate their strung out formations, to prepare an attack at Wadi Zemzem near Buerat {{convert|230|mi|km|abbr=on}} east of Tripoli.<ref>{{harvnb|Clifford|1943|pp=325–327}}</ref> Rommel had, with the agreement of Field Marshal Bastico, sent a request to the Italian ''Comando Supremo'' in Rome to [[Tunisia Campaign|withdraw to Tunisia]] where the terrain would better suit a defensive action and where he could link with the Axis army forming there, in response to the [[Operation Torch]] landings. Mussolini replied on 19 December that the [[Panzer Army Africa|Panzer Army]] must resist to the last man at Buerat.<ref name="Wa43"/>

====Tripoli====
On 15 January 1943, General Montgomery launched the 51st (Highland) Division in a frontal attack while sending the [[2nd Division (New Zealand)|2nd New Zealand Division]] and the 7th Armoured Division around the inland flank of the Axis line. Weakened by the withdrawal of 21st Panzer Division to Tunisia to strengthen [[Hans-Jürgen von Arnim|von Arnim's]] [[5th Panzer Army|Fifth Panzer Army]] (''5. Panzerarmee''), Rommel conducted a fighting retreat.<ref>{{harvnb|Watson|2007|p=44}}</ref> The port of [[Tripoli]], some {{convert|150|mi|km|abbr=on}} further west, was taken on 23 January as Rommel continued to withdraw to the French-built southern defences of Tunisia, the [[Mareth Line]].

====Tunisia====
{{main article|Tunisia Campaign}}
Rommel was by this time in contact with von Arnim's Fifth Panzer Army, which had been fighting against the multi-national [[British First Army]] in northern Tunisia, since shortly after Operation Torch the previous autumn. Hitler was determined to retain hold of Tunisia and Rommel finally started to receive replacement men and materials. The Axis now faced a war in Africa on [[two-front war|two fronts]] with Eighth Army approaching from the east and the British, French and Americans from the west. Rommel's German-Italian Panzer Army was re-named the Italian First Army under General [[Giovanni Messe]] and Rommel assumed command of the new Army Group Africa, responsible for both fronts.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} The two Allied armies were placed under [[18th Army Group]] with Harold Alexander in command. The [[Run for Tunis#Stalemate|failure]] of British First Army forces in the [[run for Tunis]] in December 1942 led to a prolongation of the [[North African campaign]] which would not end until the Italian-German forces in North Africa [[Tunisia Campaign#Axis surrender|capitulated]] in May 1943.

